{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_aetna_ver02/data/sn92051355/00393346723/1945081601/0729.xml":{"full_text":"AF of L Demands Bo!d Program\nTo Speed Up Reconversion\nExecutive Conncii Opens Session\nTFith Six-Point Pfon of yfction\nChicago\u2014The AFL Executive Council opened its sum\nmer meeting here with a ringing demand for action now to\nprevent a postwar depression.\nThe council offered the nation a challenging 6-point pro\ngram to speed up reconversion and provide for human needs.\nThis program declared:\n1\u2014 The war effort must be scaled down promptly to a\none-front basis, which would provide the military authorities\nwith more than ample support for carrying on the war against\nJapan to a quick and victorious conclusion, but would permit\nrelease of surplus men, materials and facilities for an ac\ncelerated reconversion drive.\n2\u2014 A new peace production program must be launched\nwith vigor and dispatch on a scale large enough to meet the\nnation's needs but without interference to the war effort.\n8\u2014Wartime government controls over labor and indus*\ntry must be dropped as rapidly as the war situation permits\nand an effort made to substitute voluntary, cooperative meth\nods for government directives.\n4\u2014Every reasonable encouragement should be extend\ned by the government to private industry to expand postwar\nproduction and provide full employment.\n8\u2014The present alarming shrinkage of the purchasing\npower of the nation's workers must be halted by the resto\nration of collective bargaining between labor and manage\nment.\n6\u2014Congress must act immediately after it returns from\nits summer recess to provide for human needs during recon\nversion by approving President Truman's recommendations\nfor emergency supplementation of inadequate state unem\nployment compensation, by adopting legislation for higher\nminimum wage standards, by enacting the vital Wagner\npostwar housing bill and by extending the nation's social se\ncurity system as provided under the Wagner-Murray-Dingell\nbill.\nThe council declared it will am-<\nplify its recommendations on each\nof the points of its program with\ndeclarations on specific policies to\nbe drafted during the current\nmeeting.\nAFL President William Green\naaid the council had decided to deal\nwith the reconversion problem first\nbecause it is the key to postwar\nTecovery. On this point the coun\ncil declared:\n\"America is now getting too\n!ittle reconversion. Unless prepar\nations for resumption of peacetime\nproduction are speeded up, it may\nbe too late*to avoid a major post\nwar depression. Unless more ade\nquate provision is promptly made\nfor human needs during recon\nversion, peace may bring economic\ndisaster to the American people.\nBPSTBIBS\nCLOTHKB\nCor. Bank and State Sts.\nOne Flight Up\nSUITS\nTOPCOATS\nOVERCOATS\n3R3*\n\"This tragedy must be averted.\nThe peace to which all Americans\nlook forward after four years of\nwar and sacrifice must not bear\nbitter fruit. The millions of\nAmerican young men in uniform\nwho have undergone the agony of\nmodern warfare must find oppor\ntunity, not breadlines, when they\nreturn home. The millions of war\nworkers who have labored to the\npoint of exhaustion in a victory\nproduction drive which broke all\nrecords must not be cast off with\nheartless disregard of whether or\nnot they will be able to find anoth\ner job.\n\"America cannot afford to let\nthese things happen because, if we\ndo, the American way of life will\nbe obliterated just as certainly as\nit would have been if Hitler had\nwon the war. But we won the war\nand we can also win the peace if\nwe plan intelligently and act bold\nly and confidently.\"\nMr. Green announced that the\nexecutive council had appointed\nSecretary-Treasurer George Meany j\nand Vice President William C.\nDoherty to serve as the AFL's fra\nternal delegates to the convention\nof the British Trades Union Con\ngress which will be held at Black\npool, England, next month.\nDrtnh Bottle#\nCoca-Cola Bot. Co. of New London\nINCORPORATED\nMl BANK STREET\nCor. Grace Street New London\nWIRING SUPPLIES and LIGHTING FIXTURES\nCOMPLETE LINE OF ELECTRICAL APPLIANCES\n(Soon, We Hope)\nQUICKSERVICE ELECTRICAL CO.\nM4 Main Street Est. 1922 NEW LONDON\nEiMBM!=m=m=!H=H!EM!=)H=)H=m=<H=H!S!H=m=m=!!t=H'=M)=\"!=!\"='t'='\"=\"!=!\"=\nGROTON HARDWARE CO.\n\nj MOORE'S PAINT, GLASS, BUILDERS' HARDWARE jjj\nUj\nj Phone 9649\nGroton, Conn.\n169 Thames St. !jj\nMi\nThe Yen! StioHet\n/row\nMORE BEHIND THE PRO\nDUCTION LINE STUFF What\nLEADING MAN, whose production\nrecord has fallen WAY OFF has\nto BORROW MEN from ANOTH\nER LEADING MAN in order to\nbring HIS OWN PRODUCTION\nRECORD UP TO PAR? BACK\nON THE BEAM THE BOILER\nMAKERS' Local 614, because of\nthe PLANT SHUT-DOWN will\nhold their regular monthly meeting\nfor SEPTEMBER on the Hrst free\nSaturday, September 15th.\n(This same notice will appear in\nour next two editions).\nJosephine Finnegan, Dept. 331\ntool crib, is not used to being\ncalled \"GRANDMA.\" Even though\nshe has a large family, ONE MORE\nFOR \"JOE\" to feed and take care\nof should not worry her any!\nWE HEAR THAT SOME LUCKY\nGENTS DON'T HAVE TO WORRY\nABOUT RECAPS\u2014THEY SETTLE\nFOR NEW TIRES.\nORGANIZATIONAL FLASH!\n...Victorious in an election by\na majority of nearly 4 to I, the\nINTER NATIONAL BROTHER\nHOOD OF BOILERMAKERS has\nbeen certified by the National La\nbor Relations Board as bargaining\nagency for production and main\ntenance employees of the BEALL\nPIPE and TANK CORPORATION,\nBillings, Montana.\nRUMOR HAS IT that HER\nCULES has at LONG LAST con\nsented to CLEAN OUT THE STA\nBLE OF THE GODS. Yep, BIG\nBERTHA WILL SOON BE NO\nMORE. There will be no tears,\nno sadness! BIG BERTHA'S\nINFAMOUS REPUTATION in the\nMachine Shop and on the Wet\nDock has gone from the ATLAN\nTIC TO THE PACIFIC, and\nthoughts of HER, has made many\na G. I. JOE (former E. B. em\nployees) FIGHT HARDER for a\nreal honest to God, CLEAN DEM\nOCRATIC WAY OF LIFE!\nAlong with V-J DAY this is a long\nfought for and HARD WON VIC\nTORY!\nALL those who want to drop\nPhil Santangelo a line can reach\nhim at Glenhaven Trailer Camp,\n6119 East 11th, Tulsa 15, Okla\nhoma.\nJack McClave, supervisor in\n341 Dept., and Merle Bugbee, for\nmer Paint Dept, supervisor, may\nbe able to pitch horseshoes over in\nOld Lyme but they sure have\ntheir nerve when they stacked up\nagainst those barnyard golf artists.\nJim Casey and Parker Wilde\nat the Supervisors' picnic. Jim\nand Parker are sporting their prize\nneckties\u2014Practice up a little, Jack!\nMen take for granted what is vile\nand base\nAs if themselves would do it if\nthey could,\nBut calmly sit like judges on a\ncase\nAnd wait for further proof of\nwhat is good.\nWho deals in words should weigh\nthem now and then\nUpon a scale that has a gentle\ntouch,\nAnd thus make sure he gives his\nfellow men\nNeither too little substance nor\ntoo much.\nMore and Better Flowers\nFor Less at\nCYNTHIA FLOWER SHOP\n88 Broad Street New London\nFat Haleftiras, Manager\nMiss Alberta Makar\nFor That Distinctive Haircnt\nSAM PRIOLO\nYOUR BARBER\n153 Main St. New London\nMurder im the Night\nBy CHARLES CHAPMAN\n\"Get moving,\" he ordered, jerk\ning hi* head toward the house.\n\"If you fellows have anything to\nsay, you sure are going to have the\nchance.\"\n\"Before you get too smart,\" said\nMurphy, \"you better take a look\nat this.\" He produced the deputy\nsheriffs badge that Beebe 'had\ngiven him. \"Does that tell you\nanything?\" he asked.\n\"Yes, plenty!\" It only confirmed\nthe man's suspicions regarding\nwho they were. His eyes remained\nthe same, but he drew water at\nonce. \"Why in hell didn't you say\nwho you was when I stopped you?\"\n\"We will not bother about that,\"\nMurphy said, \"Just put that rifle\nback in the boot and ride along\nwith us. I think Jack will be a lit\ntle mad with you when he hears\nhow you held us up. It could lead\nto some very unpleasant question\ning.\"\nThe man's eyes remained the\nsame, but he understood Murphy\nvery well. After a minute he\nslipped the rifle back in the boot.\n\"When you are running a few hun\ndred horses on a range you have a\nright to know who is snooping\naround,\" was his excuse for hold\ning them up.\nWhen they rode in to Jack's yard\nthe men whom they had seen come\nout of the house were all sitting\non the corral fence. They took no\nnotice of the new comers but kept\nright on talking among themselves\nand betrayed no interest whatso\never. Murphy and Pee Wee were\nnot fooled. A light haired man\ncame out of the house.\n\"Who is these fellows?\" the light\nhaired man asked.\n\"These are the two detectives\nthat were brought in on that Gar\ncia business. I didn't know who\nthey was until a few minutes ago.\nI have been trying to catch up on\nthem all morning.\"\nJack listened to what had taken\nplace and then turned to the part\nners. He said, \"I do not know what\nyou are after around here, but I\nnever had any trouble with old\nman Garcia. I make my own liv\ning, and ask no favors of anyone.\"\n\"All we want from you is a small\nbit of information,\" Murphy re\nplied. \"You have a lot of bad land\nright here by your house. We were\ntrying to find out how easy a man\ncould reach it if he had a reason\nto leave town in a hurry. Sheriff\nBeebe told us that this is the way\nthey usually go.'**\n\"Yes, and one or two of my hors\nes usually go with them! That is\nwhy I have been keeping one of\nmy boys up in the hills for the\npast few weeks.\" Jack was not\nany too friendly with the partners.\n\"I am sorry that Walenda had to\nsneak up on you that way but that\nis the way he always does.\"\nThe boys got off their horses and\nsat down on an old wagon box\nnear the kitchen door.\n\"How many men do you keep?\"\nPee Wee asked.\n\"Only half a dozen at this time.\nThese bronc busters do a lot of\ntraveling and do not stay on a\njob very long at a time. Walenda\nKing and Puza are my oldest men\nand they have been here less than\na year. Do you want to question\nthem?\"\n\"I don't believe ao,\" aaid Mur\nphy.\n\"I don't believe they know any\nthing that would help you any,\"\nsaid Jack.\n''You spoke about none of your\ncrew being away from the ranch.\nWhat about yourself? Where were\nyou the night Garcia was mur\ndered?\"\nTo be Continued\n77ie contain#\nMe %a%esf fn/orma\nMaf concerns aM\nM?or&ers.\nr\nPALMER RADIO PROGRAMS\nCONNECTICUT COLLEGE\nAugust 21, 22, 23, 1945\nWNLC\n1490 cntha dial\nPalmer Radio -Programs for\nAugust 21, 22, and 23. present stu\ndents from near and far.\nOn Tuesday evening at 7:45,\nJean Templeton of New London\nwill play a program of music for\nthe piano, Including several Cho\npin numbers. Nineteen-year-old\nJean is the daughter of Lieut. Com\nmander and Mrs. D. B. Templeton\nof 34 Post Hill Place. Before com\ning to New London she studied\nwith Vera Appleton of the Juil\nlard School of Music in New York\nCity. She attended Williams Me\nmorial Institute in New London,\nand Mount Holyoke College whdre\nshe studied with John Kirkpatrick.\nThis summer she is continuing her\nwork with Mr. Kirkpatrick in the\nSummer Session at Connecticut\nCollege.\nWednesday afternoon Palmer Ra\ndio presents Maideh Mazda whose\nhome is Teheran, Iran. Maideh is\n22 years old, and in that many\nyears, she has learned to speak\nRussian, having lived for ten years\nin Caueasia, and besides Russian\nand Persian she speaks English,\nTurkish, French and some German.\nHer main interests are languages\nand Sociology. She will be inter\nviewed by Professor Beatrice Daw\nBrown, member of the faculty at\nConnecticut College, author of nu\nmerous articles in the field of\nMiddle English and Elizabethen\nliterature. The program is heard at\n1:30 p.. m.\nOn Thursday evening at 7:45,\nRuth Kammelohr, of Mount Clair,\nNew Jersey, will interview Pro\nfessor Richard Logan, of the For\neign Area Studies at Yale Univer\nsity and geographer at Connecticut\nCollege. They will discuss GEO\nGRAPHIC FACTORS IN WORLD\nPEACE.\nThe programs are aired over\nWNLC. New London, under the\ndirection of Josephine Hunter Bay.\nLouis Levine\n/nsMrance Agrency\nK5 State Street New London, Conn.\nJFFrf, XccMcwf and Lf/# VngMrancd\nJ?ea/","height":"20619","width":"13956"}}
